    "section": "A",
    "type": "MCQ",
    "difficulty": "Medium",
    "question": "Let $x$ and $y$ be real numbers such that $50 \\left( \\frac{2x}{1 + 3i} - \\frac{y}{1 - 2i} \\right) = 31 + 17i, i = \\sqrt{-1}$. Then the value of $10(x - 3y)$ is :",
    "options": {
      "a": "20",
      "b": "31",
      "c": "35",
      "d": "75"
    },
    "correct": "d",
    "solution": "Multiply the numerators and denominators by their respective complex conjugates:\n$50 \\left( \\frac{2x(1 - 3i)}{10} - \\frac{y(1 + 2i)}{5} \\right) = 31 + 17i$\n$10x(1 - 3i) - 10y(1 + 2i) = 31 + 17i$\nEquating the real parts: $10x - 10y = 31 \\implies x - y = 3.1$\nEquating the imaginary parts: $-30x - 20y = 17 \\implies 30x + 20y = -17$\nWe solve the linear system for $x$ and $y$.\nMultiply the first equation by 3: $30x - 30y = 93$.\nSubtract it from the second equation: $(30x + 20y) - (30x - 30y) = -17 - 93 \\implies 50y = -110 \\implies y = -2.2$.\nSubstitute $y$ back: $x - (-2.2) = 3.1 \\implies x = 0.9$.\nThen we compute $10(x - 3y)$:\n$10(0.9 - 3(-2.2)) = 10(0.9 + 6.6) = 10(7.5) = 75$.",
