    "solution": "Let the limit be evaluated as $x \\to 2$. Substitute $x = 2 + h$, as $h \\to 0$.\nThe denominator becomes $D = (\\sqrt{1+h} - 1)\\log_e(1+h)$.\nUsing standard expansions or equivalents for small $h$:\n$\\sqrt{1+h} - 1 \\approx \\frac{h}{2}$ and $\\log_e(1+h) \\approx h$.\nSo, $D \\approx \\frac{h^2}{2}$. For the limit to exist and be finite ($m \\neq 0$), the numerator must be an infinitesimal of order $h^2$.\nThe numerator is $N = \\sin((2+h)^3 - 5(2+h)^2 + a(2+h) + b)$.\nLet $P(x) = x^3 - 5x^2 + ax + b$. We must have $P(2) = 0$ and $P'(2) = 0$ for $P(2+h)$ to be of order $h^2$.\n$P'(x) = 3x^2 - 10x + a$. Setting $P'(2) = 0 \\implies 12 - 20 + a = 0 \\implies a = 8$.\nSetting $P(2) = 0 \\implies 8 - 20 + 2a + b = 0 \\implies 2(8) + b = 12 \\implies 16 + b = 12 \\implies b = -4$.\nWith these values, $P(x) = x^3 - 5x^2 + 8x - 4 = (x-2)^2(x-1)$.\nThen $P(2+h) = h^2(1+h) = h^2 + h^3$.\nThe numerator limits to $\\sin(h^2 + h^3) \\approx h^2$.\nThe limit $m = \\lim_{h \\to 0} \\frac{h^2}{h^2 / 2} = 2$.\nFinally, $a + b + m = 8 + (-4) + 2 = 6$.",
