    "solution": "The coupling reaction of the given amines with benzene diazonium chloride involves electrophilic aromatic substitution on the ring attached to the nitrogen atom.\nThe reactivity depends entirely on the +M activating effect of the $-NMe_2$ group. For the $+M$ effect to operate maximally, the unhybridized p-orbital on nitrogen (containing the lone pair) must be parallel to the p-orbitals of the benzene ring.\nIn Q (one ortho methyl) and even more so in R (two ortho methyls), steric repulsion between the ortho substituents and the bulky methyl groups on the nitrogen forces the $-NMe_2$ group out of the plane of the benzene ring. \nThis phenomenon is known as Steric Inhibition of Resonance (SIR). Due to SIR, the nitrogen lone pair can no longer efficiently delocalize into the ring, drastically decreasing the ring's nucleophilicity.\nP has no ortho groups, so the group remains planar, enabling maximum +M effect.\nThus, the reactivity order decreases as steric hindrance increases: P > Q > R.",
