    "solution": "The domain of $\\cos^{-1}(y)$ is $-1 \\le y \\le 1$.\nSo, $-1 \\le \\frac{4x + 2[x]}{3} \\le 1 \\implies -3 \\le 4x + 2[x] \\le 3$.\nLet $x = I + f$, where $I = [x]$ and $f = \\{x\\}$ is the fractional part, so $0 \\le f < 1$.\nThen, $4x + 2[x] = 4(I + f) + 2I = 6I + 4f$.\nTherefore, $-3 \\le 6I + 4f \\le 3$.\nFor $I = 0$: $-3 \\le 4f \\le 3 \\implies 0 \\le f \\le \\frac{3}{4}$. So $x \\in \\left[0, \\frac{3}{4}\\right]$.\nFor $I = -1$: $-3 \\le -6 + 4f \\le 3 \\implies 3 \\le 4f \\le 9 \\implies \\frac{3}{4} \\le f < 1$. So $x \\in \\left[-\\frac{1}{4}, 0\\right)$.\nFor any other integer $I$, no such $f \\in [0, 1)$ satisfies the inequality.\nTaking the union gives the domain $x \\in \\left[-\\frac{1}{4}, \\frac{3}{4}\\right]$.\nThus, $\\alpha = -\\frac{1}{4}$ and $\\beta = \\frac{3}{4}$.\n$12(\\alpha + \\beta) = 12 \\left( -\\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{3}{4} \\right) = 12 \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\right) = 6$.",
