    "correct": "b",
    "solution": "Observe that $(x) + (x^2 - 9) = x^2 + x - 9$.\nLet $A = x$ and $B = x^2 - 9$. The given equation is $|A + B| = |A| + |B|$.\nThis property of absolute values holds true if and only if $A \\cdot B \\ge 0$.\nSubstituting the expressions back, we get: $x(x^2 - 9) \\ge 0$.\n$\\implies x(x - 3)(x + 3) \\ge 0$.\nThe critical points are $x = -3, 0, 3$. Evaluating the sign of the product in the intervals formed by these points:\nFor $x \\in [3, \\infty)$, the product is $\\ge 0$.\nFor $x \\in [-3, 0]$, the product is $\\ge 0$.\nThe solution set is $[-3, 0] \\cup [3, \\infty)$.\nComparing this with $[\\alpha, \\beta] \\cup [\\gamma, \\infty)$, we get $\\alpha = -3$, $\\beta = 0$, and $\\gamma = 3$.\nTherefore, $(\\alpha^2 + \\beta^2 + \\gamma^2) = (-3)^2 + 0^2 + 3^2 = 9 + 0 + 9 = 18$.",
