    "solution": "Comparing the degrees of both sides: $n = (n-1) + (n-2) \\implies n = 3$.\nLet $f(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d$. Since $f(0) = 0 \\implies d = 0$.\n$f'(x) = 3ax^2 + 2bx + c$ and $f''(x) = 6ax + 2b$.\nSubstitute into $f(x) = f'(x)f''(x)$:\n$ax^3 + bx^2 + cx = (3ax^2 + 2bx + c)(6ax + 2b) = 18a^2 x^3 + 18ab x^2 + (4b^2 + 6ac) x + 2bc$.\nComparing coefficients:\n$a = 18a^2 \\implies a = \\frac{1}{18}$ (since degree is 3, $a \\neq 0$).\n$b = 18ab \\implies 1 = 18a$ (which matches).\n$c = 4b^2 + 6ac \\implies c = 4b^2 + \\frac{1}{3}c \\implies \\frac{2}{3}c = 4b^2 \\implies c = 6b^2$.\nConstant term $0 = 2bc$. If $b = 0$, then $c = 0$.\nSo, $f(x) = \\frac{x^3}{18}$.\nWe have $f'(x) = \\frac{x^2}{6}$ and $f''(x) = \\frac{x}{3}$.\nCalculate the required values at $x=2$:\n$f'(2) = \\frac{4}{6} = \\frac{2}{3}$.\n$f''(2) = \\frac{2}{3}$.\n$\\int_0^2 f(x) dx = \\int_0^2 \\frac{x^3}{18} dx = \\left[ \\frac{x^4}{72} \\right]_0^2 = \\frac{16}{72} = \\frac{2}{9}$.\nFinally: $36 \\left( \\frac{2}{3} + \\frac{2}{3} + \\frac{2}{9} \\right) = 36 \\left( \\frac{14}{9} \\right) = 4 \\times 14 = 56$.",
