    "question": "A coin is tossed 8 times. If the probability that exactly 4 heads appear in the first six tosses and exactly 3 heads appear in the last five tosses is $p$, then $96p$ is equal to \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_.",
    "options": null,
    "correct": "$9$",
    "solution": "Let $H$ denote getting a head. Total coin tosses = 8 (numbered $T_1$ to $T_8$).\nThe overlap between the first six tosses and the last five tosses is $T_4, T_5, T_6$ (3 tosses).\nLet the number of heads in the overlapping section ($T_4, T_5, T_6$) be $k$, where $k \\in \\{0, 1, 2, 3\\}$.\nThe remaining tosses are $T_1, T_2, T_3$ (3 tosses) and $T_7, T_8$ (2 tosses).\nTo have exactly 4 heads in $T_1 \\dots T_6$, there must be $4-k$ heads in $T_1 \\dots T_3$.\nTo have exactly 3 heads in $T_4 \\dots T_8$, there must be $3-k$ heads in $T_7 \\dots T_8$.\nFor valid combinations:\n$0 \\le 4-k \\le 3 \\implies k \\ge 1$.\n$0 \\le 3-k \\le 2 \\implies 1 \\le k \\le 3$.\nSo $k \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$.\nThe probability for a specific $k$ is:\n$P(k) = \\binom{3}{4-k}(1/2)^3 \\times \\binom{3}{k}(1/2)^3 \\times \\binom{2}{3-k}(1/2)^2 = \\frac{\\binom{3}{4-k} \\binom{3}{k} \\binom{2}{3-k}}{2^8}$.\nEvaluating for each $k$:\nFor $k = 1$: $\\binom{3}{3} \\binom{3}{1} \\binom{2}{2} = 1 \\times 3 \\times 1 = 3$.\nFor $k = 2$: $\\binom{3}{2} \\binom{3}{2} \\binom{2}{1} = 3 \\times 3 \\times 2 = 18$.\nFor $k = 3$: $\\binom{3}{1} \\binom{3}{3} \\binom{2}{0} = 3 \\times 1 \\times 1 = 3$.\nTotal numerator $= 3 + 18 + 3 = 24$.\n$p = \\frac{24}{2^8} = \\frac{24}{256} = \\frac{3}{32}$.\n$96p = 96 \\left(\\frac{3}{32}\\right) = 3 \\times 3 = 9$.",
