    "correct": "$3$",
    "solution": "First, evaluate the magnitudes:\n$|\\vec{a}_k|^2 = \\tan^2 \\theta_k + 1 = \\sec^2 \\theta_k$.\n$|\\vec{b}_k|^2 = 1 + \\cot^2 \\theta_k = \\csc^2 \\theta_k$.\nSo we seek the ratio $\\frac{\\sum_{k=1}^n \\sec^2 \\theta_k}{\\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k}$.\nWe have the identity: $\\csc^2 x - \\sec^2 x = \\csc^2 x - \\frac{1}{\\sin^2 x - \\sin^4 x} = 4\\cot^2 2x$. Differentiating the identity $\\cot x - \\tan x = 2\\cot 2x$ yields $\\csc^2 x + \\sec^2 x = 4\\csc^2 2x$.\nRearranging gives: $\\sec^2 x = 4\\csc^2 2x - \\csc^2 x$.\nApplying this to our sum: $\\sum_{k=1}^n \\sec^2 \\theta_k = 4 \\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2(2\\theta_k) - \\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k$.\nNotice $2\\theta_k = 2^k \\frac{\\pi}{2^n+1} = \\theta_{k+1}$. Therefore, $4\\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_{k+1}$.\nFor $k=n$, $2\\theta_n = \\frac{2^n \\pi}{2^n+1} = \\pi - \\frac{\\pi}{2^n+1} = \\pi - \\theta_1$.\nSince $\\csc^2(\\pi - \\theta_1) = \\csc^2 \\theta_1$, the term cycles back.\nHence, $\\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_{k+1} = \\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k$.\nSo $\\sum_{k=1}^n \\sec^2 \\theta_k = 4\\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k - \\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k = 3\\sum_{k=1}^n \\csc^2 \\theta_k$.\nThe ratio is exactly $3$.",
