    "solution": "1. Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene gives Toluene.\n2. Chlorination ($Cl_2 / FeCl_3$) of toluene gives mainly p-chlorotoluene due to steric factors favouring the para position.\n3. Oxidation with strong acidic $K_2Cr_2O_7$ turns the methyl group into a carboxylic acid, yielding p-chlorobenzoic acid as Product X.\nMolecular formula for p-chlorobenzoic acid is $C_7H_5O_2Cl$. Molar Mass = $(12 \\times 7) + 5 + (16 \\times 2) + 35.5 = 156.5$ g/mol.\nReaction with $NaHCO_3$: $\\text{R-COOH} + NaHCO_3 \\to \\text{R-COONa} + H_2O + CO_2\\uparrow$.\n$1$ mole of carboxylic acid produces $1$ mole of $CO_2$ gas.\nAt STP, 1 mole of an ideal gas occupies roughly $22.4$ L (or dm$^3$).\n$11.2$ dm$^3$ of $CO_2$ translates to $\\frac{11.2}{22.4} = 0.5$ moles of $CO_2$, which equates to requiring $0.5$ moles of Product X.\nMass $P = 0.5 \\text{ moles} \\times 156.5 \\text{ g/mol} = 78.25$ g.",
