    "correct": "$5$",
    "solution": "Molar mass of $AgBr = 108 + 80 = 188$ g/mol.\nMoles of $AgBr = \\frac{3.36}{188} \\approx 0.01787$ mol. Since one mole of AgBr has one mole of Br, there are $0.01787$ moles of Br atoms.\nMass of Br in the sample = $0.01787 \\times 80 = 1.4298$ g.\nPercentage of Br in compound $X = \\frac{1.4298}{2.0} \\times 100 \\approx 71.49\\%$.\nGiven Percentage of C = $26.7\\%$.\nAssuming it's a simple bromo hydrocarbon, Percentage of H = $100 - (71.49 + 26.7) = 1.81\\%$.\nRelative number of moles (dividing % by atomic masses):\nMoles of C = $26.7 / 12 = 2.225$\nMoles of H = $1.81 / 1 = 1.81$\nMoles of Br = $71.49 / 80 = 0.8936$\nSimplifying the ratio by dividing by the smallest value ($0.8936$):\nC: $2.225 / 0.8936 \\approx 2.49 \\approx 2.5$\nH: $1.81 / 0.8936 \\approx 2.02 \\approx 2$\nBr: $0.8936 / 0.8936 = 1$\nTo eliminate fractions, multiply entirely by 2: Ratio becomes C:$5$, H:$4$, Br:$2$.\nThe empirical formula is $C_5H_4Br_2$, carrying 5 Carbon atoms.",
